    aim: "An in-depth reference for medical secretaries, consultant PAs, private practice administrators and gastroenterology coordinators — covering anatomy, terminology, procedures, investigations, cancer pathways and private practice administration specific to gastroenterology.",
    sections: [
      { heading: "1. Introduction to Gastroenterology for Medical Secretaries", body: "<p>Gastroenterology is the medical specialty dealing with the digestive system including the oesophagus, stomach, bowel, liver, pancreas and gallbladder.</p><p><strong>Common pathways:</strong></p><ul><li>GP referral</li><li>Consultant outpatient review</li><li>Blood/stool testing</li><li>Imaging</li><li>Endoscopy</li><li>Diagnosis</li><li>Treatment</li><li>Long-term monitoring</li></ul><p><strong>Common documents:</strong></p><ul><li>Clinic letters</li><li>Endoscopy reports</li><li>Colonoscopy reports</li><li>Histology results</li><li>Imaging reports</li><li>MDT letters</li><li>Insurance reports</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "2. Gastroenterology Anatomy Terminology", body: "<ul><li><strong>Oesophagus</strong> — Food pipe.</li><li><strong>Stomach</strong> — Digestion organ.</li><li><strong>Small bowel</strong> — Absorbs nutrients.</li><li><strong>Colon</strong> — Large bowel.</li><li><strong>Rectum</strong> — Final part of bowel.</li><li><strong>Liver</strong> — Processes nutrients/toxins.</li><li><strong>Gallbladder</strong> — Stores bile.</li><li><strong>Pancreas</strong> — Produces digestive enzymes.</li><li><strong>Bile duct</strong> — Carries bile.</li><li><strong>Anus</strong> — End of digestive tract.</li><li><strong>GI tract</strong> — Gastrointestinal system.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "3. Common Gastroenterology Conditions Dictionary", body: "<p><strong>Upper GI:</strong></p><ul><li>GORD — Acid reflux disease.</li><li>Gastritis — Stomach inflammation.</li><li>Peptic ulcer disease — Ulcers in stomach/bowel.</li></ul><p><strong>Bowel:</strong></p><ul><li>IBS — Irritable bowel syndrome.</li><li>Crohn's disease — Inflammatory bowel disease.</li><li>Ulcerative colitis — Large bowel inflammation.</li><li>Diverticular disease — Bowel pouch condition.</li></ul><p><strong>Liver:</strong></p><ul><li>Fatty liver disease.</li><li>Hepatitis.</li><li>Cirrhosis.</li></ul><p><strong>Other:</strong></p><ul><li>Coeliac disease.</li><li>Bowel polyps.</li><li>Bowel cancer.</li><li>Pancreatitis.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "4. Gastroenterology Abbreviations &amp; Acronyms", body: "<ul><li><strong>GI</strong> — Gastrointestinal</li><li><strong>UGI</strong> — Upper gastrointestinal</li><li><strong>LGI</strong> — Lower gastrointestinal</li><li><strong>IBS</strong> — Irritable bowel syndrome</li><li><strong>IBD</strong> — Inflammatory bowel disease</li><li><strong>UC</strong> — Ulcerative colitis</li><li><strong>GORD</strong> — Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease</li><li><strong>OGD</strong> — Oesophago-gastro-duodenoscopy</li><li><strong>ERCP</strong> — Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography</li><li><strong>EUS</strong> — Endoscopic ultrasound</li><li><strong>FIT</strong> — Faecal immunochemical test</li><li><strong>LFT</strong> — Liver function test</li><li><strong>ALT</strong> — Liver enzyme</li><li><strong>MDT</strong> — Multidisciplinary team</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "5. Investigation Dictionary", body: "<p><strong>Blood Tests:</strong></p><ul><li>FBC — Checks anaemia/infection.</li><li>LFT — Assesses liver function.</li><li>CRP — Inflammation marker.</li><li>Coeliac screen — Checks for coeliac disease.</li></ul><p><strong>Stool Tests:</strong></p><ul><li>FIT — Detects hidden blood.</li><li>Faecal calprotectin — Inflammation marker.</li></ul><p><strong>Procedures:</strong></p><ul><li>Gastroscopy — Camera test of oesophagus/stomach.</li><li>Colonoscopy — Camera test of large bowel.</li><li>Flexible sigmoidoscopy — Lower bowel camera test.</li></ul><p><strong>Imaging:</strong> Ultrasound, CT abdomen, MRI/MRCP.</p>" },
      { heading: "6. Procedures &amp; Operations Dictionary", body: "<ul><li><strong>Gastroscopy (OGD)</strong> — Camera examination of upper digestive tract.</li><li><strong>Colonoscopy</strong> — Camera examination of large bowel.</li><li><strong>Flexible sigmoidoscopy</strong> — Lower bowel examination.</li><li><strong>ERCP</strong> — Bile duct investigation/treatment.</li><li><strong>Polypectomy</strong> — Removal of bowel polyps.</li><li><strong>Biopsy</strong> — Tissue sample.</li><li><strong>Capsule endoscopy</strong> — Swallowed camera test.</li><li><strong>PEG insertion</strong> — Feeding tube placement.</li></ul><p><strong>Secretary checks:</strong> Procedure type, preparation instructions, insurance authorisation, follow-up, histology tracking.</p>" },
      { heading: "7. Gastroenterology Clinic Letter Structure", body: "<p><strong>Typical sections:</strong></p><ul><li>Presenting complaint</li><li>GI symptoms</li><li>Past history</li><li>Medication</li><li>Examination</li><li>Investigations</li><li>Diagnosis</li><li>Management plan</li></ul><p><strong>Example phrases:</strong></p><ul><li>&ldquo;The patient presents with abdominal pain.&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;Colonoscopy demonstrated&hellip;&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;Biopsies were taken.&rdquo;</li><li>&ldquo;I have arranged follow-up after results.&rdquo;</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "8. Common Dictation Phrases Explained", body: "<ul><li><strong>Altered bowel habit</strong> — Change in bowel pattern.</li><li><strong>Dysphagia</strong> — Difficulty swallowing.</li><li><strong>PR bleeding</strong> — Bleeding from rectum.</li><li><strong>Benign polyp</strong> — Non-cancerous growth.</li><li><strong>Await histology</strong> — Waiting for tissue analysis.</li><li><strong>Surveillance colonoscopy</strong> — Routine monitoring test.</li><li><strong>Conservative management</strong> — Non-procedure treatment.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "9. Medication Reference", body: "<ul><li><strong>PPIs</strong> — Reduce stomach acid.</li><li><strong>Laxatives</strong> — Treat constipation.</li><li><strong>Anti-diarrhoeal medication</strong> — Controls diarrhoea.</li><li><strong>Steroids</strong> — Reduce inflammation.</li><li><strong>Biologics</strong> — Specialist IBD treatments.</li><li><strong>Immunosuppressants</strong> — Reduce immune activity.</li><li><strong>Antibiotics</strong> — Treat infections.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "10. Gastroenterology Cancer Pathway Terms", body: "<ul><li><strong>2 Week Wait</strong> — Urgent suspected cancer referral.</li><li><strong>MDT</strong> — Specialist cancer discussion.</li><li><strong>Biopsy</strong> — Tissue sample.</li><li><strong>Histology</strong> — Microscope diagnosis.</li><li><strong>Staging</strong> — Cancer extent.</li><li><strong>Surveillance</strong> — Regular monitoring.</li><li><strong>Oncology referral</strong> — Cancer specialist involvement.</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "11. Procedure Booking Terminology", body: "<ul><li><strong>GA</strong> — General anaesthetic</li><li><strong>LA</strong> — Local anaesthetic</li><li><strong>Sedation</strong> — Relaxing medication</li><li><strong>Bowel prep</strong> — Cleansing before colonoscopy</li><li><strong>Consent</strong> — Patient agreement</li><li><strong>Day case</strong> — Home same day</li><li><strong>Follow-up</strong> — Review appointment</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "12. Private Practice Administration", body: "<p><strong>Secretary checks:</strong></p><ul><li>Insurance details</li><li>Authorisation</li><li>Endoscopy approvals</li><li>Imaging approvals</li><li>Histology tracking</li><li>Follow-up appointments</li><li>Procedure preparation instructions</li></ul>" },
      { heading: "13. Dictation Cheat Sheet", body: "<p>Common words to recognise in gastroenterology dictation:</p><ul><li>Colonoscopy</li><li>Gastroscopy</li><li>Endoscopy</li><li>Biopsy</li><li>Histology</li><li>Polyp</li><li>Bowel</li><li>Colon</li><li>Liver</li><li>Pancreas</li><li>Reflux</li><li>Inflammation</li><li>Crohn's</li><li>Colitis</li></ul>" },
    ],
